Vector — the default indexed sequence.

A vector is internally a balanced thirty-two-way tree. From the outside it behaves like an array. From the inside, the tree is so shallow that indexed access at any position is effectively constant time, even for a very large vector. In practice you can treat vector access as constant time and not worry about it.

Random access, appending, prepending, and the updated method are all effectively constant time. The operators have a small mnemonic — the colon always sits next to the collection. So vector-colon-plus-element is an append, because the colon is next to the vector, and element-plus-colon-vector is a prepend, by the same logic. And the updated method returns a new vector with one position changed, leaving the original untouched.

Reach for vector when you need indexed access with a mix of prepend and append, or simply when you do not yet know what your access pattern will be. The rule of thumb is this — when in doubt between list and vector, pick vector. Pick list only when you specifically want cons-cell ergonomics for recursion or pattern matching.
